Tensor-native shared-memory sample
=================================

Kernel tensor subsystem
-----------------------

Native tensor objects are implemented as a kernel subsystem under
`kernel/tensor/`, selected with `CONFIG_TENSOR_SUBSYSTEM`. The
`CONFIG_TENSOR_NATIVE` module provides `/dev/tensor_native`, fd-backed object
lifecycle, validated layouts, mmap, synchronization, DMA-BUF interchange,
kernel mappings, resource accounting, and tracepoints. Networking remains a
sample consumer of this common subsystem rather than owning tensor objects.

Native allocations are charged to both the creator UID and its default cgroup.
The `uid_limit_bytes` and `cgroup_limit_bytes` module parameters enforce hard
limits, while `/proc/tensor_native_accounting` reports total and scoped usage.
Run the quota test after loading the core module:

	sudo samples/tensor_native/test_accounting.sh

This sample demonstrates a zero-copy tensor handoff between processes:

producer -> shared memory tensor object -> consumer

Build:

	make -C samples/tensor_native

Run in two terminals:

	./samples/tensor_native/producer /tensor0 64 64
	./samples/tensor_native/consumer /tensor0

Cleanup:

	rm -f /dev/shm/tensor0

Notes:
- Data path is mmap-based (no serialization/parsing of tensor payload).
- Kernel and SHM paths share `include/uapi/linux/tensor_native.h` for the
  shape/dtype/strides/version contract.
- SHM transport state (`seq` and `ready`) follows the common tensor header.
- Consumers validate metadata, layout extents, and mapped-buffer bounds.
- A lightweight seq/ready handshake provides consistency.

Validate the shared-memory ABI and bounds checks:

	make -C samples/tensor_native check

Kernel-managed tensor objects
-----------------------------

Enable `CONFIG_TENSOR_NATIVE`, build and load the kernel or module, then run:

	make -C samples/tensor_native tensor_object_test
	sudo insmod samples/tensor_native/tensor_native-wsl-6.6.87.2.ko
	sudo insmod samples/tensor_native/tensor_kernel_consumer.ko
	sudo ./samples/tensor_native/tensor_object_test
	sudo rmmod tensor_kernel_consumer tensor_native

The test creates a validated anonymous tensor fd through
`/dev/tensor_native`, maps its payload, clones a storage-sharing view, exports
the storage as a DMA-BUF, and imports that DMA-BUF as another tensor object.
It also passes a tensor fd to a child process with `SCM_RIGHTS` and validates
shared data and generation signaling across the process boundary.

The `tensor_kernel_consumer` sample module accepts that same fd through an
ioctl, resolves it with the exported kernel tensor API, maps the payload with
DMA synchronization, reads a value, and signals a new generation.

Native Netfilter tensor producer
--------------------------------

`tensor_net_producer.ko` hooks IPv4 `PRE_ROUTING` only in the network namespace
of the process issuing `TENSOR_NET_BIND` and writes packet features directly
into a contiguous
`u32[slots,batch,8]` tensor. Each full slot gets its own sequence and signals
the tensor fd. Networking fills later slots while userspace processes earlier
ones. Captures are dropped only when the producer reaches an unacknowledged
slot; packets themselves continue normally.

Bindings can select an ingress interface, IP protocol, source port, and
destination port. Zero leaves a field unfiltered. Producer state, tensor
handles, queues, hooks, filters, and statistics are independently allocated
for every network namespace.

Each namespace exposes a read-only `/proc/net/tensor_net_producer` snapshot.
It reports bind and verdict mode, ring positions, active filters, pending
packets, capture totals, verdict totals, and timeout totals. Reading through
`ip netns exec` selects that namespace's producer state:

	ip netns exec <name> cat /proc/net/tensor_net_producer

The `TENSOR_NET` Generic Netlink family provides namespace-aware `BIND`,
`UNBIND`, and `GET_STATS` control operations. The `events` multicast group
publishes completed-batch and packet-timeout notifications. Tensor dequeue and
acknowledgement remain ioctls because they are latency-sensitive data-plane
operations. Existing ioctl bind and stats commands remain supported.

Query the current namespace through the dependency-free sample client:

	sudo samples/tensor_native/tensor_net_ctl stats
	sudo samples/tensor_native/tensor_net_ctl unbind

The family and multicast group can be inspected with iproute2:

	genl ctrl list | grep -A8 TENSOR_NET

Set `TENSOR_NET_CONTROL=genl` to make `tensor_net_capture` perform bind,
statistics, and unbind through Generic Netlink. Dequeue and acknowledgement
continue through the data-plane ioctl interface:

	sudo env TENSOR_NET_CONTROL=genl \
		samples/tensor_native/tensor_net_capture 64 4 20 verdict

The dual-namespace test runs its left producer through Generic Netlink and its
right producer through compatibility ioctls.

Run two concurrent isolated namespace producers with different ring layouts:

	sudo samples/tensor_native/test_netns.sh

Namespace teardown cancels timeout work, unregisters the namespace hook, and
reinjects every queued packet fail-open before releasing tensor handles.

Tensor tracepoints
------------------

The `tensor_native` trace system reports object creation and release, sequence
signals, queued packets, completed batches, verdicts, and enforcement
timeouts. Events include object or storage identity, network namespace inode,
packet ID, ring position, verdict source, and sequence where applicable.

Run the tracefs validation harness after loading both modules:

	sudo samples/tensor_native/test_trace.sh

For continuous inspection, enable the event system and read `trace_pipe`:

	echo 1 | sudo tee /sys/kernel/tracing/events/tensor_native/enable
	sudo cat /sys/kernel/tracing/trace_pipe

Load the modules and run the loopback traffic harness:

	sudo insmod samples/tensor_native/tensor_native-wsl-6.6.87.2.ko
	sudo insmod samples/tensor_native/tensor_net_producer.ko
	sudo samples/tensor_native/tensor_net_capture 256 4 100
	sudo rmmod tensor_net_producer tensor_native

The harness generates loopback UDP traffic, validates each signaled tensor
batch, acknowledges it, and reports packets per second.

Tensor verdict enforcement
--------------------------

Binding an additional contiguous `u8[slots,batch]` verdict tensor enables
bounded asynchronous enforcement. Feature column 7 contains a nonzero packet
ID. The producer owns at most 4096 queued packets, and `TENSOR_NET_ACK` applies
the corresponding verdict slot (`0` accepts, `1` drops) before reinjecting the
packets after the Tensor Netfilter hook.

The queue fails open: packets are accepted when allocation fails, when a
decision exceeds the configured timeout, or when the tensors are unbound.
Timeout, accepted, and verdict-drop counts are exposed through
`TENSOR_NET_GET_STATS`.

Run the enforcement test, which drops alternating loopback packet IDs:

	sudo samples/tensor_native/tensor_net_capture 128 4 100 verdict

Netfilter sidecar simulation
----------------------------

This is the first network subsystem slice:

packet feature tensor -> policy sidecar -> verdict tensor

`nf_packet_producer` now builds raw IPv4/TCP packet bytes and runs a
`packet bytes -> tensor row` adapter before publishing to shared memory.

Build:

	make -C samples/tensor_native

Run in two terminals:

	./samples/tensor_native/nf_policy_consumer /pkt0 /verdict0
	./samples/tensor_native/nf_packet_producer /pkt0 /verdict0 1024

Persistent mode (for accurate perf):

	./samples/tensor_native/nf_policy_consumer /pkt0 /verdict0 200
	./samples/tensor_native/nf_packet_producer /pkt0 /verdict0 1024 200

Benchmark:

	./samples/tensor_native/bench_persistent.sh

Byte-path baseline and comparison
---------------------------------

Baseline run (packet bytes parsed in consumer):

	./samples/tensor_native/nf_bytes_consumer /pkt0 /verdict0 200
	./samples/tensor_native/nf_bytes_producer /pkt0 /verdict0 1024 200

Tensor vs bytes benchmark:

	./samples/tensor_native/bench_compare.sh

Live NFQUEUE ingress (optional)
-------------------------------

Build (requires `libnetfilter_queue` dev package):

	make -C samples/tensor_native nfq_tensor_verdict

Example traffic hook (IPv4 TCP ingress to NFQUEUE 0):

	sudo iptables -I INPUT -p tcp -j NFQUEUE --queue-num 0

Run verdict bridge:

	./samples/tensor_native/nf_policy_consumer /pkt0 /verdict0 0
	sudo ./samples/tensor_native/nfq_tensor_verdict 0 /pkt0 /verdict0

Cleanup iptables rule:

	sudo iptables -D INPUT -p tcp -j NFQUEUE --queue-num 0

Expected output:
- nfqueue bridge prints accepted/dropped counts
- consumer runs until interrupted

Cleanup:

	rm -f /dev/shm/pkt0 /dev/shm/verdict0

Tensor-native layer design
--------------------------

Current state in this sample:
- Data plane uses POSIX SHM + mmap with a stable tensor header.
- Producers/consumers agree on tensor metadata (`shape`, `dtype`, `stride_bytes`).
- Synchronization uses a simple `seq`/`ready` handshake.
- NFQUEUE can emit the same tensor metadata ABI with a fixed packet-feature
  tensor payload.
- `CONFIG_TENSOR_NATIVE` provides fd-backed, kernel-managed tensor objects.
- Object payloads are mapped with `mmap`; generation changes use ioctl wait,
  signal, and poll instead of userspace spin loops.

Remaining target state:
- Programs exchange tensor handles instead of byte blobs.
- Subsystems (network, IO, ML sidecars) attach to the same tensor object.

Object model
------------

Each tensor object has:
- identity: anonymous fd ownership and fd-passing semantics.
- layout: ndim, dtype, shape, stride_bytes, data_offset, data_bytes.
- storage: refcounted vmalloc pages or an imported DMA-BUF.
- sync state: sequence counter, wait queue, and poll readiness.
- lifetime: refcounted object; memory released when last ref is dropped.

Minimal ABI direction
---------------------

The control fd (`/dev/tensor_native`) implements:
- `TENSOR_CREATE`: create object with validated metadata and size.
- `TENSOR_IMPORT_DMABUF`: wrap a DMA-BUF in validated tensor metadata.

Tensor object fds implement:
- `TENSOR_GET_INFO`: fetch immutable metadata and current sync state.
- `TENSOR_SIGNAL`: publish a completed write generation.
- `TENSOR_WAIT`: block/poll for next generation (or timeout).
- `TENSOR_CLONE_VIEW`: create a shape/stride view without copying storage.
- `TENSOR_EXPORT_DMABUF`: expose vmalloc-backed storage to DMA-BUF consumers.
- `TENSOR_BEGIN_ACCESS` / `TENSOR_END_ACCESS`: bracket CPU access and wait for
  implicit DMA-BUF reservation fences while applying exporter cache handling.

Kernel consumers use `tensor_native_get()`, `tensor_native_map()`,
`tensor_native_unmap()`, and `tensor_native_signal()` from
`include/linux/tensor_native.h`.

Data movement:
- `mmap(object_fd)` maps tensor payload directly.
- Metadata is retrieved with `TENSOR_GET_INFO`.
- Mappings are page-granular. A sub-page view reports its payload start in
  `data_offset`; callers must access only the declared payload range.

Concurrency semantics
---------------------

Current first contract:
- Writers publish strictly increasing generation numbers.
- One or more readers can wait or poll for a later generation.
- Writer protocol: write payload -> release store on `seq` publish.
- Reader protocol: acquire load `seq` -> read payload -> optional recheck `seq`.
- If `seq` changes during read, reader retries (seqlock-like).

This preserves zero-copy while avoiding coarse locks for steady-state inference.

Security and isolation
----------------------

- The control device defaults to mode `0600`.
- Object access is controlled by fd ownership and explicit fd passing.
- Objects are limited to 64 MiB and total live storage to 256 MiB.
- Namespace, cgroup, and LSM policy integration remains future work.

Networking integration path
---------------------------

Phase 1 (already prototyped):
- NFQUEUE copies packet payload to userspace and adapter emits feature tensor row.

Phase 2:
- NFQUEUE/NAPI path emits tensor descriptor sidecar plus shared payload handle.
- Userspace policy engine reads tensor directly and returns verdict tensor handle.

Phase 3:
- In-kernel policy path consumes same tensor format for hot-path decisions.
- Userspace remains control/training plane, kernel uses cached model artifacts.

Milestones
----------

1. Done: fd-based object creation and mmap.
2. Done: `TENSOR_WAIT`, `TENSOR_SIGNAL`, and poll synchronization.
3. Done: shared metadata ABI and validation.
4. Convert networking paths from copied Netlink tensors to object fds.
5. Add view/subtensor support for batched pipelines without copies.
6. Add namespace/cgroup accounting, LSM hooks, and pressure metrics.
